\title{Constant Time Testing}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Constant-time testing detects timing side channels in cryptographic code. Use when auditing crypto implementations for timing vulnerabilities.}

\subtree{
\title{Constant-Time Testing}
\p{Timing attacks exploit variations in execution time to extract secret information from cryptographic implementations. Unlike cryptanalysis that targets theoretical weaknesses, timing attacks leverage implementation flaws - and they can affect any cryptographic code.}

\subtree{
\title{Background}
\p{Timing attacks were introduced by [Kocher](https://paulkocher.com/doc/TimingAttacks.pdf) in 1996. Since then, researchers have demonstrated practical attacks on RSA ([Schindler](https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/3-540-44499-8_8.pdf)), OpenSSL ([Brumley and Boneh](https://crypto.stanford.edu/~dabo/papers/ssl-timing.pdf)), AES implementations, and even post-quantum algorithms like [Kyber](https://eprint.iacr.org/2024/1049.pdf).}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\pre{\startverb
| Concept | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Constant-time | Code path and memory accesses independent of secret data |
| Timing leakage | Observable execution time differences correlated with secrets |
| Side channel | Information extracted from implementation rather than algorithm |
| Microarchitecture | CPU-level timing differences (cache, division, shifts) |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Why This Matters}
\p{Timing vulnerabilities can:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Expose private keys} - Extract secret exponents in RSA/ECDH}
\li{\strong{Enable remote attacks} - Network-observable timing differences}
\li{\strong{Bypass cryptographic security} - Undermine theoretical guarantees}
\li{\strong{Persist silently} - Often undetected without specialized analysis}
}

\p{Two prerequisites enable exploitation:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Access to oracle} - Sufficient queries to the vulnerable implementation}
\li{\strong{Timing dependency} - Correlation between execution time and secret data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Constant-Time Violation Patterns}
\p{Four patterns account for most timing vulnerabilities:}

\pre{\startverb
// 1. Conditional jumps - most severe timing differences
if(secret == 1) { ... }
while(secret > 0) { ... }

// 2. Array access - cache-timing attacks
lookup_table[secret];

// 3. Integer division (processor dependent)
data = secret / m;

// 4. Shift operation (processor dependent)
data = a << secret;
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Conditional jumps} cause different code paths, leading to vast timing differences.}

\p{\strong{Array access} dependent on secrets enables cache-timing attacks, as shown in [AES cache-timing research](https://cr.yp.to/antiforgery/cachetiming-20050414.pdf).}

\p{\strong{Integer division and shift operations} leak secrets on certain CPU architectures and compiler configurations.}

\p{When patterns cannot be avoided, employ [masking techniques](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-38348-9_9) to remove correlation between timing and secrets.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example: Modular Exponentiation Timing Attacks}
\p{Modular exponentiation (used in RSA and Diffie-Hellman) is susceptible to timing attacks. RSA decryption computes:}

\pre{\startverb
$$ct^{d} \mod{N}$$
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
where $d$ is the secret exponent. The *exponentiation by squaring* optimization reduces multiplications to $\log{d}$:
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
$$ \begin{align*} & \textbf{Input: } \text{base }y,\text{exponent } d=\{d_n,\cdots,d_0\}_2,\text{modulus } N \\ & r = 1 \\ & \textbf{for } i=|n| \text{ downto } 0: \\ & \quad\textbf{if } d_i == 1: \\ & \quad\quad r = r * y \mod{N} \\ & \quad y = y * y \mod{N} \\ & \textbf{return }r \end{align*} $$
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
The code branches on exponent bit $d_i$, violating constant-time principles. When $d_i = 1$, an additional multiplication occurs, increasing execution time and leaking bit information.
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
Montgomery multiplication (commonly used for modular arithmetic) also leaks timing: when intermediate values exceed modulus $N$, an additional reduction step is required. An attacker constructs inputs $y$ and $y'$ such that:
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
$$ \begin{align*} y^2 < y^3 < N \\ y'^2 < N \leq y'^3 \end{align*} $$
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
For $y$, both multiplications take time $t_1+t_1$. For $y'$, the second multiplication requires reduction, taking time $t_1+t_2$. This timing difference reveals whether $d_i$ is 0 or 1.
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\p{\strong{Apply constant-time analysis when:}}

\ul{
\li{Auditing cryptographic implementations (primitives, protocols)}
\li{Code handles secret keys, passwords, or sensitive cryptographic material}
\li{Implementing crypto algorithms from scratch}
\li{Reviewing PRs that touch crypto code}
\li{Investigating potential timing vulnerabilities}
}

\p{\strong{Consider alternatives when:}}

\ul{
\li{Code does not process secret data}
\li{Public algorithms with no secret inputs}
\li{Non-cryptographic timing requirements (performance optimization)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Reference}
\pre{\startverb
| Scenario | Recommended Approach | Skill |
|----------|---------------------|-------|
| Prove absence of leaks | Formal verification | SideTrail, ct-verif, FaCT |
| Detect statistical timing differences | Statistical testing | **dudect** |
| Track secret data flow at runtime | Dynamic analysis | **timecop** |
| Find cache-timing vulnerabilities | Symbolic execution | Binsec, pitchfork |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Constant-Time Tooling Categories}
\p{The cryptographic community has developed four categories of timing analysis tools:}

\pre{\startverb
| Category | Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|----------|------|------|
| **Formal** | Mathematical proof on model | Guarantees absence of leaks | Complexity, modeling assumptions |
| **Symbolic** | Symbolic execution paths | Concrete counterexamples | Time-intensive path exploration |
| **Dynamic** | Runtime tracing with marked secrets | Granular, flexible | Limited coverage to executed paths |
| **Statistical** | Measure real execution timing | Practical, simple setup | No root cause, noise sensitivity |
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{1. Formal Tools}
\p{Formal verification mathematically proves timing properties on an abstraction (model) of code. Tools create a model from source/binary and verify it satisfies specified properties (e.g., variables annotated as secret).}

\p{\strong{Popular tools:}}

\ul{
\li{[SideTrail](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/tree/main/tests/sidetrail)}
\li{[ct-verif](https://github.com/imdea-software/verifying-constant-time)}
\li{[FaCT](https://github.com/plsyssec/fact)}
}

\p{\strong{Strengths:} Proof of absence, language-agnostic (LLVM bytecode) \strong{Weaknesses:} Requires expertise, modeling assumptions may miss real-world issues}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Symbolic Tools}
\p{Symbolic execution analyzes how paths and memory accesses depend on symbolic variables (secrets). Provides concrete counterexamples. Focus on cache-timing attacks.}

\p{\strong{Popular tools:}}

\ul{
\li{[Binsec](https://github.com/binsec/binsec)}
\li{[pitchfork](https://github.com/PLSysSec/haybale-pitchfork)}
}

\p{\strong{Strengths:} Concrete counterexamples aid debugging \strong{Weaknesses:} Path explosion leads to long execution times}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Dynamic Tools}
\p{Dynamic analysis marks sensitive memory regions and traces execution to detect timing-dependent operations.}

\p{\strong{Popular tools:}}

\ul{
\li{[Memsan](https://clang.llvm.org/docs/MemorySanitizer.html): [Tutorial](https://crocs-muni.github.io/ct-tools/tutorials/memsan)}
\li{\strong{Timecop} (see below)}
}

\p{\strong{Strengths:} Granular control, targeted analysis \strong{Weaknesses:} Coverage limited to executed paths}

\blockquote{\strong{Detailed Guidance:} See the \strong{timecop} skill for setup and usage.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Statistical Tools}
\p{Execute code with various inputs, measure elapsed time, and detect inconsistencies. Tests actual implementation including compiler optimizations and architecture.}

\p{\strong{Popular tools:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{dudect} (see below)}
\li{[tlsfuzzer](https://github.com/tlsfuzzer/tlsfuzzer)}
}

\p{\strong{Strengths:} Simple setup, practical real-world results \strong{Weaknesses:} No root cause info, noise obscures weak signals}

\blockquote{\strong{Detailed Guidance:} See the \strong{dudect} skill for setup and usage.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Testing Workflow}
\pre{\startverb
Phase 1: Static Analysis        Phase 2: Statistical Testing
┌─────────────────┐            ┌─────────────────┐
│ Identify secret │      →     │ Detect timing   │
│ data flow       │            │ differences     │
│ Tool: ct-verif  │            │ Tool: dudect    │
└─────────────────┘            └─────────────────┘
         ↓                              ↓
Phase 4: Root Cause             Phase 3: Dynamic Tracing
┌─────────────────┐            ┌─────────────────┐
│ Pinpoint leak   │      ←     │ Track secret    │
│ location        │            │ propagation     │
│ Tool: Timecop   │            │ Tool: Timecop   │
└─────────────────┘            └─────────────────┘
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Recommended approach:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Start with dudect} - Quick statistical check for timing differences}
\li{\strong{If leaks found} - Use Timecop to pinpoint root cause}
\li{\strong{For high-assurance} - Apply formal verification (ct-verif, SideTrail)}
\li{\strong{Continuous monitoring} - Integrate dudect into CI pipeline}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tools and Approaches}
\subtree{
\title{Dudect - Statistical Analysis}
\p{[Dudect](https://github.com/oreparaz/dudect/) measures execution time for two input classes (fixed vs random) and uses Welch's t-test to detect statistically significant differences.}

\blockquote{\strong{Detailed Guidance:} See the \strong{dudect} skill for complete setup, usage patterns, and CI integration.}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start for Constant-Time Analysis}
\pre{\startverb
#define DUDECT_IMPLEMENTATION
#include "dudect.h"

uint8_t do_one_computation(uint8_t *data) {
    // Code to measure goes here
}

void prepare_inputs(dudect_config_t *c, uint8_t *input_data, uint8_t *classes) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < c->number_measurements; i++) {
        classes[i] = randombit();
        uint8_t *input = input_data + (size_t)i * c->chunk_size;
        if (classes[i] == 0) {
            // Fixed input class
        } else {
            // Random input class
        }
    }
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key advantages:}}

\ul{
\li{Simple C header-only integration}
\li{Statistical rigor via Welch's t-test}
\li{Works with compiled binaries (real-world conditions)}
}

\p{\strong{Key limitations:}}

\ul{
\li{No root cause information when leak detected}
\li{Sensitive to measurement noise}
\li{Cannot guarantee absence of leaks (statistical confidence only)}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Timecop - Dynamic Tracing}
\p{[Timecop](https://post-apocalyptic-crypto.org/timecop/) wraps Valgrind to detect runtime operations dependent on secret memory regions.}

\blockquote{\strong{Detailed Guidance:} See the \strong{timecop} skill for installation, examples, and debugging.}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start for Constant-Time Analysis}
\pre{\startverb
#include "valgrind/memcheck.h"

#define poison(addr, len) VALGRIND_MAKE_MEM_UNDEFINED(addr, len)
#define unpoison(addr, len) VALGRIND_MAKE_MEM_DEFINED(addr, len)

int main() {
    unsigned long long secret_key = 0x12345678;

    // Mark secret as poisoned
    poison(&secret_key, sizeof(secret_key));

    // Any branching or memory access dependent on secret_key
    // will be reported by Valgrind
    crypto_operation(secret_key);

    unpoison(&secret_key, sizeof(secret_key));
}
\stopverb}

\p{Run with Valgrind:}

\pre{\startverb
valgrind --leak-check=full --track-origins=yes ./binary
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key advantages:}}

\ul{
\li{Pinpoints exact line of timing leak}
\li{No code instrumentation required}
\li{Tracks secret propagation through execution}
}

\p{\strong{Key limitations:}}

\ul{
\li{Cannot detect microarchitecture timing differences}
\li{Coverage limited to executed paths}
\li{Performance overhead (runs on synthetic CPU)}
}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Implementation Guide}
\subtree{
\title{Phase 1: Initial Assessment}
\p{\strong{Identify cryptographic code handling secrets:}}

\ul{
\li{Private keys, exponents, nonces}
\li{Password hashes, authentication tokens}
\li{Encryption/decryption operations}
}

\p{\strong{Quick statistical check:}}

\ol{
\li{Write dudect harness for the crypto function}
\li{Run for 5-10 minutes with \code{\startverb timeout 600 ./ct_test\stopverb}}
\li{Monitor t-value: high absolute values indicate leakage}
}

\p{\strong{Tools:} dudect \strong{Expected time:} 1-2 hours (harness writing + initial run)}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Detailed Analysis}
\p{If dudect detects leakage:}

\p{\strong{Root cause investigation:}}

\ol{
\li{Mark secret variables with Timecop \code{\startverb poison()\stopverb}}
\li{Run under Valgrind to identify exact line}
\li{Review the four common violation patterns}
\li{Check assembly output for conditional branches}
}

\p{\strong{Tools:} Timecop, compiler output (\code{\startverb objdump -d\stopverb})}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Remediation}
\p{\strong{Fix the timing leak:}}

\ul{
\li{Replace conditional branches with constant-time selection (bitwise operations)}
\li{Use constant-time comparison functions}
\li{Replace array lookups with constant-time alternatives or masking}
\li{Verify compiler doesn't optimize away constant-time code}
}

\p{\strong{Re-verify:}}

\ol{
\li{Run dudect again for extended period (30+ minutes)}
\li{Test across different compilers and optimization levels}
\li{Test on different CPU architectures}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Continuous Monitoring}
\p{\strong{Integrate into CI:}}

\ul{
\li{Add dudect tests to test suite}
\li{Run for fixed duration (5-10 minutes in CI)}
\li{Fail build if leakage detected}
}

\p{See the \strong{dudect} skill for CI integration examples.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Vulnerabilities}
\pre{\startverb
| Vulnerability | Description | Detection | Severity |
|---------------|-------------|-----------|----------|
| Secret-dependent branch | `if (secret_bit) { ... }` | dudect, Timecop | CRITICAL |
| Secret-dependent array access | `table[secret_index]` | Timecop, Binsec | HIGH |
| Variable-time division | `result = x / secret` | Timecop | MEDIUM |
| Variable-time shift | `result = x << secret` | Timecop | MEDIUM |
| Montgomery reduction leak | Extra reduction when intermediate > N | dudect | HIGH |
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{Secret-Dependent Branch: Deep Dive}
\p{\strong{The vulnerability:} Execution time differs based on whether branch is taken. Common in optimized modular exponentiation (square-and-multiply).}

\p{\strong{How to detect with dudect:}}

\pre{\startverb
uint8_t do_one_computation(uint8_t *data) {
    uint64_t base = ((uint64_t*)data)[0];
    uint64_t exponent = ((uint64_t*)data)[1]; // Secret!
    return mod_exp(base, exponent, MODULUS);
}

void prepare_inputs(dudect_config_t *c, uint8_t *input_data, uint8_t *classes) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < c->number_measurements; i++) {
        classes[i] = randombit();
        uint64_t *input = (uint64_t*)(input_data + i * c->chunk_size);
        input[0] = rand(); // Random base
        input[1] = (classes[i] == 0) ? FIXED_EXPONENT : rand(); // Fixed vs random
    }
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{How to detect with Timecop:}}

\pre{\startverb
poison(&exponent, sizeof(exponent));
result = mod_exp(base, exponent, modulus);
unpoison(&exponent, sizeof(exponent));
\stopverb}

\p{Valgrind will report:}

\pre{\startverb
Conditional jump or move depends on uninitialised value(s)
  at 0x40115D: mod_exp (example.c:14)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Related skill:} \strong{dudect}, \strong{timecop}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Case Studies}
\subtree{
\title{Case Study: OpenSSL RSA Timing Attack}
\p{Brumley and Boneh (2005) extracted RSA private keys from OpenSSL over a network. The vulnerability exploited Montgomery multiplication's variable-time reduction step.}

\p{\strong{Attack vector:} Timing differences in modular exponentiation \strong{Detection approach:} Statistical analysis (precursor to dudect) \strong{Impact:} Remote key extraction}

\p{\strong{Tools used:} Custom timing measurement \strong{Techniques applied:} Statistical analysis, chosen-ciphertext queries}
}

\subtree{
\title{Case Study: KyberSlash}
\p{Post-quantum algorithm Kyber's reference implementation contained timing vulnerabilities in polynomial operations. Division operations leaked secret coefficients.}

\p{\strong{Attack vector:} Secret-dependent division timing \strong{Detection approach:} Dynamic analysis and statistical testing \strong{Impact:} Secret key recovery in post-quantum cryptography}

\p{\strong{Tools used:} Timing measurement tools \strong{Techniques applied:} Differential timing analysis}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Usage}
\subtree{
\title{Tips and Tricks}
\pre{\startverb
| Tip | Why It Helps |
|-----|--------------|
| Pin dudect to isolated CPU core (`taskset -c 2`) | Reduces OS noise, improves signal detection |
| Test multiple compilers (gcc, clang, MSVC) | Optimizations may introduce or remove leaks |
| Run dudect for extended periods (hours) | Increases statistical confidence |
| Minimize non-crypto code in harness | Reduces noise that masks weak signals |
| Check assembly output (`objdump -d`) | Verify compiler didn't introduce branches |
| Use `-O3 -march=native` in testing | Matches production optimization levels |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Mistakes}
\pre{\startverb
| Mistake | Why It's Wrong | Correct Approach |
|---------|----------------|------------------|
| Only testing one input distribution | May miss leaks visible with other patterns | Test fixed-vs-random, fixed-vs-fixed-different, etc. |
| Short dudect runs (< 1 minute) | Insufficient measurements for weak signals | Run 5-10+ minutes, longer for high assurance |
| Ignoring compiler optimization levels | `-O0` may hide leaks present in `-O3` | Test at production optimization level |
| Not testing on target architecture | x86 vs ARM have different timing characteristics | Test on deployment platform |
| Marking too much as secret in Timecop | False positives, unclear results | Mark only true secrets (keys, not public data) |
\stopverb}
}
}

